  "why": "The paper proposes CAGFuzz, which uses a generative model (AEG, based on CycleGAN) to create adversarial images by adding small, 'not human-observable' perturbations. The entire generation and training process described operates on continuous, floating-point representations of images. The paper does not mention any explicit steps to enforce input format constraints, such as clipping pixel values to the valid [0, 255] range or rounding them to integer precision. Since generative models typically output floating-point tensors, these small perturbations are highly susceptible to being altered or completely lost when the image tensor is serialized into a standard integer-based format (e.g., PNG, JPEG) for storage or real-world use. This standard serialization process, which is a necessary step to feed an image file to a deployed system, would involve rounding and clipping that the method does not account for. Consequently, failures triggered by such fine-grained, floating-point perturbations may not be reproducible.",
